liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The operator of the Indonesia hospital in Gaza has denied accusations that its facility has been used by Hamas to launch an attacks. The comments were in response to the Israeli military's repeated accusation that Hamas uses hospitals, including Gaza's main hospital al-Shifa, the Qatari-funded Sheikh Hamad Hospital and a hospital built by groups from Indonesia, as cover to shield its underground operations. "We built this hospital to help others, according to the needs of the Gazans," said Sarbini Abdul Murad, the chairman of MER-C, a voluntary group operating the Indonesia hospital. "Israel's accusation is a precondition so that they can attack the Indonesian hospital in Gaza," he told a press conference in the Indonesian capital of Jakarta. Israel's military spokesperson on Sunday claimed one satellite image had shown rocket launchers located across the street from the Indonesian hospital. Another official at MER-C said there was no tunnel under the hospital and that its fuel tank and power generators are kept in separate nearby buildings for security reasons. Indonesia, the world's biggest Muslim-majority country, has called for an immediate ceasefire and has sent humanitarian aid to Gaza. Reuters
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Indonesia group denies hospital used by Hamas network

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The health ministry in the Gaza Strip says an Israeli air strike hit a building in the Al Shifa hospital complex, killing one Palestinian, but Israel has denied it targeted the hospital. Gaza's health ministry spokesman said 170 patients and hundreds of displaced Palestinians were in the hospital building at the time. He said several Palestinians were wounded in the strike. But an Israeli military spokesperson, when asked about the claim, said: "There was no IDF (Israel Defense Forces) strike on the Shifa hospital." Earlier, Al Jazeera TV and Hamas-affiliated Al Aqsa radio said Israeli forces had targeted a solar panel system at the hospital complex. Chief IDF spokesperson Rear Admiral Daniel Hagari, asked about those reports during a briefing with reporters, said: "We didn't attack, to the best of my knowledge, solar panels in the Shifa hospital." Israel's military has previously presented alleged evidence showing some hospitals are used by Hamas as bases of operation but these claims cannot be independently verified. Reuters

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Labor MP Bill Shorten has called the federal Greens "opportunists" after they walked out of the Senate in support of Palestinians yesterday. During Senate Question Time, senator Mehreen Faruqi declared the Greens brought the "people's protest" into parliament after leading her colleagues in a walkout. Senator Janet Rice raised a printed page showing the Palestinian flag as they walked out. Mr Shorten this morning said no one thinks this move helps. "I don't think the Greens walking out helps a single soul anywhere. I think that is just political grand standing. I don't know how that helps," he said "I think that the Government has the right line of length. We want to make sure that we are supporting the humanitarian pause. "We want to see relief get through to innocent Palestinian civilians. "But you know, with the Greens … they don't walk out over Hamas. So I think that these guys are opportunists." He said the Australian government's messaging on the issue is right. "This most recent shocking conflict was triggered by Hamas crossing the borders into Israel," he said. "I think the government has made its position clear that Israel has a right to defend itself. "We also want to make sure that, to the extent that it is possible, the rules of war are followed. "That means these civilians, these Palestinian civilians, it's not their fault. It's shameful. What we're seeing is very difficult too." You can read more about what transpired yesterday here:
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Bill Shorten: Greens walkout 'political grand standing'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It's been hard to miss the news from overnight that Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has met with Chinese President Xi Jinping — the first time an Australian leader has visited China in seven years. It was also a meeting 18 months in the making to stabilise the relationship between the two, especially when it comes to trade. Geoff Raby, former Australian ambassador to China, says the Australia-China trade relationship will continue to go from strength to strength, and bilateral relations have returned to "normal". You can watch his full chat with The Business host Kirsten Aiken below: You can also read a full recap of Albanese and Xi's meeting from our East Asia correspondent Kathleen Calderwood here:

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian share market is likely to slip in morning trade, snapping its five-day winning streak. ASX futures were down 0.2%, following a subdued performance on Wall Street overnight. US markets have just finished trading, with the Dow Jones, S & P 500 and Nasdaq Composite rising 0.1%, 0.2% and 0.3% respectively. The main US stock indexes were trading in the red, until they made a final-hour recovery. Last week, the S & P climbed 5.9% and the Nasdaq surged 6.6% (marking their best weeks since November 2022). The Dow jumped 5.1% last week (its biggest weekly gain since October 2022) on hopes the US Federal Reserve is near the end of its rate-hiking cycle.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Wall Street extends gains, ASX to open lower
